another GREAT episode, as i sat there waiting for my heating to come on and the wind is howling outside .....

probably as the "cyberman" was coming through, he was effecting the spooky of the ACTUAL ghosts in the house, and maybe explains the skeleton hands and skull moving too as that didn't connect to the main story!


however maybe that was also reanimating the ye olde soldiers bones .....

A REAL GHOST STORY double cross over!

yeah the cybranium was protecting itself from these rouge ones ..... who's the bad guys in this on eh?

basically the doc was in a no-win situation, so she took the logical solution, and into a KNOWN SITUATION!

just a few loose ends really, the reveal of the fam at the window ..... AAAAGGGGHHHH ..... oh can we come in?
having the skeleton hand and skull actually moving in the crib
yasmin being a bit too know-it-all during her little talk
"cyberman" felt and sounded a bit too tim shaw

apart from that it was a well produced well written episode ..... and a TWO PARTER TOO!

snippet.textDisplay:
There is so much that is being changed through the timeline of planet Earth, eventually, the timeline will just ripple, crack and fall apart and the Earth will just fall in on itself. As there is only so much of history you can see, there is only so much that can be changed. If something changes too often it won't be the same anymore. So at any point in Doctor Who, will we finally see the Earth destroyed? My point being that most episodes are based on or about Earth, the amount that the doctor has changed and seen. There will come a time where she would have seen everything...


I mean why not right? Humans probably would have survived everything with the help of the doctor from time to time, so they would have spread across the stars and found new planets to colonize. In future series, the doctor could have companions that come from different worlds, like maybe a time lord companion or a human from the future maybe. The destruction of the Earth is long overdue.

snippet.textDisplay:
Marvelous episode, nothing more to say about it! There were a few loose ends that only add to the mystery factor, but ultimately very enjoyable and stimulating! A Haunting of Hill House-eske historical episode filled with perception filters (I think Moffat would be proud, and the presentation of the effects was gorgeous), there's also the main storyline intertwined at the heart of the mystery making this a sort of 3-parter finale when I was expecting it to be the next one and... actual gh-ghosts? (or were they images created by the Cyberium inside Shelley... who knows? Sorry Graham, you gotta live with that explanation mate xD). Btw, I think this is one element that was missing in series 11 and I think it adds up a lot of value to the more casual episodes - a lot of stories are tied to the main story in very interesting and unique ways. Sometimes directly related, sometimes indirectly. I think it's a nice side snack.

Loved every single character, and props to Maxine Alderton for writing an exquisite, terrifying and mistifying episode which did break the mold of some pre-finale stories that often tend to feel a bit stagnant in comparison to the finales (the previous story also achieved that imo, if you consider this the unofficial first part of the finale). This is how you make a pre-finale and set up the mood. I was setting up for a nice horror vibe story (which I wouldn't mind), but ended up loving the appearance of the Lone Cyberman - and he's definitely more frightening than I thought it would be. And that impossible scenario at the end with that speech from the Doctor... dear lord, that was powerful stuff.

snippet.textDisplay:
A truly fantastic episode leading towards the finale

Speaking of, I have a theory:

The Judoon were contracted by the Time Lords to retrieve the Ruth Doctor; Gaz was sent to oversee the mission, but let a personal vendetta get in the way.
Anyway, the Time Lords wanted Ruth Doctor to end the threat of the Cyber army. She does so with the 13th Doctor, but is killed in the process.
In order to keep the timeline in check, the Time Lords give Ruth Doctor a new life cycle (becoming William Hartnell) and erase her memory to keep the consistency with the 13th Doctor's memories.
Ruth Doctor is the Timeless Child as she never truly dies; the Timeless Child being a name the Cybermen give her (like the Oncoming Storm from the Daleks).
When the Master discovered this, he flew into a rage at the fact the Time Lords interfered when their law was always to not get involved, while they also lengthened the life of his nemesis, thus he took it out be destroying them.

Plenty of holes as of now, I know, but that's the fun with theories 😎

Look forward to the finale. Thanks for reading
